nal|author=Hilsdale, Cecily J. |year=2008 |title=The Social Life of the Byzantine Gift: The Royal Crown of Hungary Re-Invented |journal=Art History |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=602\u2013631 |url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/academia.edu.documents/30927763/Hilsdale_RoyalCrownofHungary.pdf?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAJ56TQJRTWSMTNPEA&Expires=1460065062&Signature=8fnM5w5w7OYNRqTAhP5WF%2BYLCPU%3D&response-content-disposition=inline%3B%20filename%3DThe_Social_Life_of_the_Byzantine_Gift_Th.pdf |doi=10.1111/j.1467-8365.2008.00634.x |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407204342/http://s3.amazonaws.com/academia.edu.documents/30927763/Hilsdale_RoyalCrownofHungary.pdf?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAJ56TQJRTWSMTNPEA&Expires=1460065062&Signature=8fnM5w5w7OYNRqTAhP5WF+YLCPU%3D&response-content-disposition=inline%3B+filename%3DThe_Social_Life_of_the_Byzantine_Gift_Th.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |df= }}\n* {{Cite book|author=Kelleher, Patrick J. |year=1951 |title=The Holy Crown of Hungary, Rome |publisher=American Academy in Rome |oclc=603872168}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Holy Crown of Hungary}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060403170223/http://kep.tar.hu/mollach/50217849 The Holy Crown of Hungary (images)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071028093910/http://kep.tar.hu/mollach/50283816#2 Sceptre (images)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060624004443/http://kep.tar.hu/mollach/50283774#2 The crown jewels (images)]\n{{Wikisource|Eine Kr\u00f6nung von Volkes Gnaden|Eine Kr\u00f6nung von Volkes Gnaden|H. v. C., illustriert, in ''[[Die Gartenlaube]]'' (1867), Heft 30}}\n* {{Hl-Lex|b|Stephan_I_von_Ungarn.htm|Stephan I of Hungary}}\n* [http://www.fotomarburg.de/gaeste/szelenyi/index.html Exhibition of the Holy Crown of Hungary]\n\n{{crowns}}\n{{Crown jewels by country}}\n{{National symbols of Hungary}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holy Crown Of Hungary}}\n[[Category:Individual crowns|Hungary]]\n[[Category:Kingdom of Hungary]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Regalia]]\n[[Category:State ritual and ceremonies]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:Crowns of the coat of Arms of Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:Medieval crowns]]\n[[Category:Byzantine art]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1100-1110 \u2192 1100\u20131110, \u2019s \u2192 's (7)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holy_Crown_of_Hungary"}
{"title_page": "Dustin Hoffman filmography", "text_new": "[[File:Dustin Hoffman Cannes.jpg|alt=Dustin Hoffman at Cannes|thumb|Dustin Hoffman at Cannes]]\nAmerican actor [[Dustin Hoffman]] began his career by appearing in an episode of ''[[Naked City (TV series)|Naked City]]'' in 1961. His first theatrical performance was 1961's ''A Cook for Mr. General'' as Ridzinski. Following several guest appearances on television, he starred in the 1966 play ''[[Eh? (play)|Eh?]]''; his performance garnered him both a [[Theatre World Award]] and [[Drama Desk Award]].<ref name=\"Playbill\">{{cite web|title=Dustin Hoffman|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/dustin-hoffman-vault-0000015166|website=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Hoffman made his film debut in 1967 when he appeared in the comedy ''[[The Tiger Makes Out]]''. In the same year, his breakthrough role as Benjamin \"Ben\" Braddock, the title character in [[Mike Nichols]]' comedy-drama ''[[The Graduate]]'', led to Hoffman achieving star status and his first [[Academy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"Biography.com\">{{cite web|author=Biography.com Editors|title=Dustin Hoffman Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/dustin-hoffman-9341124#acting-career|website=[[Biography.com]]|publisher=[[A&E Television Networks]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424235902/http://www.biography.com/people/dustin-hoffman-9341124#acting-career|archive-date=April 24, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He then acted in the play ''Jimmy Shine'' as the eponymous character and the comedy film ''[[Madigan's Millions]]'' (both 1968). In 1969, he starred alongside [[Jon Voight]] in the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] winner ''[[Midnight Cowboy]]'', which Hoffman was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] a second time.<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/>\n\nThe 1970s saw Hoffman star in several critically acclaimed and commercially successful films, including the Western ''[[Little Big Man (film)|Little Big Man]]'' (1970), psychological thriller ''[[Straw Dogs (1971 film)|Straw Dogs]]'' (1971), prison film ''[[Papillon (1973 film)|Papillon]]'' (1973) alongside [[Steve McQueen]], ''[[Lenny (film)|Lenny]]'' (1974) about the controversial comedian [[Lenny Bruce]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Canby|first1=Vincent|title='Lenny,' With Dustin Hoffman, Is One --Fourth Brilliant|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9404E4D9133BE63BBC4952DFB767838F669EDE|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=November 11, 1974}}</ref> and the political thriller ''[[All the President's Men (film)|All the President's Men]]'' (1976) as journalist [[Carl Bernstein]] investigating the [[Watergate scandal]] alongside [[Bob Woodward]] (played by Robert Redford).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tunzelmann|first1=Alex von|title=All the President's Men: Hoffman and Redford fight the powers that be|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/10/all-the-presidents-men-watergate-conspiracy-richard-nixon-woodward-bernstein-redford-hoffman|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> After starring in the suspense-thriller ''[[Marathon Man (film)|Marathon Man]]'' (1976) and the crime drama ''[[Straight Time]]'' (1978), Hoffman starred in the 1979 drama ''[[Kramer vs. Kramer]]'', which he won the Academy Award for Best Actor for the first time for his performance as Ted Kramer.<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/>\n\nAfter a three-year acting hiatus, he starred in the comedy ''[[Tootsie]]'' in 1982 as a struggling actor who pretends to be a woman in order to get an acting role. He returned to stage acting with a 1984 performance as [[Willy Loman]] in ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' \u2013 Hoffman reprised the role a year later in a television film.<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/> 1987 saw the release of originally ill-received comedy ''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'', in which he starred with [[Warren Beatty]]; its critical support has since grown.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brody|first1=Richard|title=To Wish Upon Ishtar|url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/to-wish-upon-ishtar|website=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 9, 2010}}</ref> He won his second Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal of the [[autistic]] savant Ray Babbitt in the 1988 film ''[[Rain Man]]'', co-starring [[Tom Cruise]].<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/>  In 1989, he was nominated for a [[Tony Award]] and a Drama Desk Award for playing [[Shylock]] in a stage performance of ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]''.<ref name=\"Playbill\"/> In the 1990s, he made appearances in such film as [[Warren Beatty]]'s action comedy adaptation ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' (1990), [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]]'' (1991) as [[Captain Hook]], guest starred in the 1991 \"[[Lisa's Substitute]]\" episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', medical disaster ''[[Outbreak (film)|Outbreak]]'' (1995), legal crime drama ''[[Sleepers (film)|Sleepers]]'' (1996), thriller ''[[Mad City (film)|Mad City]]'' (1997), and the satirical black comedy ''[[Wag the Dog]]'' (1997) alongside [[Robert De Niro]].\n\nIn the 2000s, he played theatrical producer [[Charles Frohman]] in ''[[Finding Neverland (film)|Finding Neverland]]'', co-starred in the comedy ''[[Meet the Fockers]]'' (both 2004) as Bernie Focker, the fantasy thriller ''[[Perfume: The Story of a Murderer (film)|Perfume: The Story of a Murderer]]'' (2006), and played the title character in the family comedy ''[[Mr. Magorium's Wonder Emporium]]'' (2007). Hoffman has acted in the ''[[Kung Fu Panda (franchise)|Kung Fu Panda]]'' franchise since 2008 and reprised his role as Focker in ''[[Little Fockers]]'' (2010). He starred in the [[HBO]] drama series ''[[Luck (TV series)|Luck]]'', which was cancelled after one season due to animal safety concerns, and made his directorial debut in 2012 with ''[[Quartet (2012 film)|Quartet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=French|first1=Phillip|title=Quartet \u2013 review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jan/06/quartet-review-film-dustin-hoffman|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=January 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\n[[File:Dustin Hoffman - Little Big Man.jpg|thumb|Hoffman in 1968]]\n[[File:Hoffman-Midler - 1977.jpg|thumb|With [[Bette Midler]] on Bette Midler TV Special (1977)]]\n[[File:Dustin Hoffman - Salesman.jpg|thumb|in ''Death of a Salesman'' (1985)]]\n[[File:Dustin Hoffman Quartet avp 2013.jpg|thumb|Hoffman in Paris at the French premiere of  ''[[Quartet (2012 film)|Quartet]]'', March 2013]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+ Film credits of Dustin Hoffman\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" width=20% | Title\n!scope=\"col\" width=1% | Year\n!scope=\"col\" width=15% | Role\n!scope=\"col\" width=15% | Director(s)\n!scope=\"col\" width=10% class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n!scope=\"col\" width=2% class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Tiger Makes Out]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1967\n| Hap\n| [[Arthur Hiller]]\n| \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|title=Dustin Hoffman filmography (as of award year)|url=http://www.afi.com/laa/laa99f.aspx|website=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Graduate]]''\n| Benjamin \"Ben\" Braddock\n| [[Mike Nichols]]\n|  \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Madigan's Millions]]''\n| 1968\n| Jason Fister\n| [[Stanley Prager]]\n| \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Midnight Cowboy]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1969\n| Enrico Salvatore \"Ratso\" Rizzo\n| [[John Schlesinger]]\n|        \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[John and Mary (film)|John and Mary]]''\n| John\n| [[Peter Yates]]\n|             \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Little Big Man (film)|Little Big Man]]''\n| 1970\n| Jack Crabb\n| [